## Complete Example

**Q**: How manage position when VaR breached 3 days running, volatility +40%, correlation to SPX rising from 0.3 to 0.7?

**Difficulty**: A | **Domain**: Risk Management, Portfolio Management  
**Key Insight**: Tests crisis risk response; distinguishes systematic risk managers from reactive traders.

**Answer** (285w):  
**Context**: VaR breach 3× + vol +40% + correlation 0.3→0.7 signals regime shift—diversification breakdown and elevated tail risk [Ref: G2, G6, A5].

**Analysis**: Root causes [Ref: L4]: (1) Vol regime change (low→high); VaR model calibrated on past [Ref: G2]; (2) Correlation spike (crisis contagion) undermines diversification [Ref: A10]; (3) Position concentration or factor crowding [Ref: L3]. Decompose: check factor exposures [Ref: G13, G15], Greeks [Ref: G3], stress scenarios [Ref: A7].

**Reasoning**: VaR assumes normal distribution—fails in fat tails [Ref: L2, A2]. 3× breach = model failure or structural change. Rising SPX correlation means systematic risk dominates [Ref: G5, L1]. Vol +40% increases tail risk exponentially (gamma/convexity effects) [Ref: G3, L2]. Must recalibrate risk model [Ref: T2] and reduce exposure immediately [Ref: A7].

**Recommendations**: 3-phase crisis protocol [Ref: L4, A11]: (1) Day 1: Cut gross exposure 30% (liquidate lowest-conviction, most-correlated positions) [Ref: L3]; hedge systematic risk (SPX puts, VIX calls) [Ref: G3, L2]; (2) Day 2-3: Recalibrate VaR with recent 60d data + stress scenarios (2008, 2020) [Ref: T2, A7]; calculate CVaR for tail beyond VaR [Ref: L2]; (3) Week 1-2: Rebalance to target risk (reduce factor concentration <40% single factor) [Ref: G15]; improve diversification (lower correlation assets) [Ref: L5].

**Implementation**: Emergency risk committee daily 1-wk, then weekly [Ref: A11]. Real-time Greeks monitoring [Ref: T1]. CRO approval for deviations. Expect PnL hit -5-10% from deleveraging/hedging costs.

**Metrics**: VaR compliance >95%, CVaR <15%, correlation to SPX <0.5, max DD <20%, factor concentration <40%.

**When NOT**: If vol spike is transient event-driven (single stock, no contagion) vs. regime shift [Ref: L4]; or if selling into panic creates worse losses.

**Limitations**: VaR recalibration has estimation error [Ref: A2]; hedges costly (vol premium 20-30%) [Ref: L2]; deleveraging locks in losses; correlation may persist 3-6mo [Ref: A10]. Real-time data lags; execution slippage in volatile markets [Ref: T1]. CVaR needs sufficient tail data [Ref: L2]. Crisis requires judgment beyond models [Ref: L4, A11].

